>	      		<h2 class="title"> 		  <a href="#"> Introduction </a> 		</h2>		<p class="meta"><span class="date">July, 2014</span><span class="posted">Posted by <a href="#">James</a></span></p>		<div style="clear: both;">&nbsp;</div>		<div class="entry">		  Dear Colleague,		  		  <p>		    Here we introduce the General-HANDS data-set. Our		    objective is to provide a standard		    dataset on which to evaluate hand detection & pose estimation		    systems. The dataset aims to encompass a complete variety of		    sequences, demonstrating different view-points,		    scales, poses, occlusions, and camera technologies. We have captured 22		    of our own sequences and welcome outside		    contributions. 		  </p>		  <p>		    We are happy to run your code on these		    sequences if you will provide us an implementation (in		    either executable or source form). Otherwise,		    We supplicate you to submit results on any of the		    following challenges for 		    whichever subset of the sequences you feel to		    be appropriate for your algorithm (to		    jsupanci@uci.edu). 		  </p>		  <ol>		    <li>		      Hand Detection: for each image produce a file		      containing one line per detection (eg output_$ID.txt). Each line		      should contain 4 numbers indicating the center		      of the hand: x, y (in pixels), z (in cm) and a confidence.		    </li>		    <li>		      Hand Key-point localization: as above, but		      additionally append an x,y,z,r value for each		      key point to the detection line. The key-points are as		      follows (Common		      Name/<a href="http://www.libhand.org/"> libhand </a> name/Abbreviation: 		      <ol>			<li> pinky-tip / NA / F11 </li> 			<li> pinky-knuckle / finger1joint3 / F13 </li>			<li> pinky-base / finger1joint1 / F4 </li>			<li> ring-tip / NA / F21 </li>			<li> ring-knuckle / finger2joint3 / F23 </li>			<li> ring-base / finger2joint1 / F24 </li> 			<li> middle-tip / NA / F31 </li>			<li> middle-knuckle / finger3joint3 / F33</li>			<li> middle-base / finger3joint1 / F34 </li>			<li> index-tip / NA / F41 </li>			<li> index-knuckle / finger4joint3 / F43 </li>			<li> index-base / finger4joint1 / F44 </li> 			<li> thumb-tip / NA / F51 </li>			<li> thumb-knuckle / finger5joint3 / F52 </li>			<li> thumb-base / finger5joint2 / F53 </li>			<li> palm-center / Bone / P2 </li>			<li> wrist / Metacarpals / P1 </li>		      </ol>		      <p>			To clarify the format, we give several ground			truth annotations (click on the image for the			expected output). 		      </p>		      <p>			<a href="annotation/gt_00500.csv">			<img src="annotation/OCCLUSION2_500.png" width="200" /> </a>			<a href="annotation/gt_00620.csv">			<img src="annotation/EX_HCI_FAR3_00620.png" width="200" /></a>			<a href="annotation/gt_01020.csv">			<img src="annotation/OCCLUSION1_1020.png" width="200" /></a>		      </p>		    </li>		    <li>		      Semantic Segmentation. For each image, produce		      an RGB image with the following semantic		      segmentation.		      <p>			<img src="segmentation.png" />		      </p>		    </li>		  </ol>		    		  		  <br> Kind Regards, </br>		  <br> James Supancic III </br>		  <br> Gregory Rogez </br>		  <br> Deva Ramanan </br>		</div>	      </div>	      <div>		<div class="post" id="IndexOfSequences">		  <h2 class="title"> 			    <a href="#"> Index of Sequences </a>		  </h2>		  <div class="entry">		  		    <table class="tg">		      <tr>			<th class="tg-031e">Sequence Title</th>			<th class="tg-031e">Camera Type</th>			<th class="tg-031e">Sign Language</th>			<th class="tg-031e">Gestures</th>			<th class="tg-031e">Activities &amp; Objects</th>			<th class="tg-031e">Egocentric Activities</th>			<th class="tg-031e">Supervisory Viewpoints</th>		      </tr>		      <tr>		      			<td> 			  <a href="#EGOCENTRIC0 Intel/Creative"> 			    <p>EGOCENTRIC0 Intel/Creative</p>			  </a>			</td> 			<td>Intel/Creative</td>			<td>no</td>			<td>no</td>			<td>yes</td>			<td>yes</td>			<td>no</td>		      </tr><tr>		      			<td> 			  <a href="#EGOCENTRIC1 Intel/Creative"> 			    <p>EGOCENTRIC1 Intel/Creative</p>			  </a>			</td> 			<td>Intel/Creative</td>			<td>no</td>			<td>no</td>			<td>yes</td>			<td>yes</td>			<td>no</td>		      </tr><tr>		      			<td> 			  <a href="#EGOCENTRIC2 Intel/Creative"> 			    <p>EGOCENTRIC2 Intel/Creative</p>			  </a>			</td> 			<td>Intel/Creative</td>			<td>no</td>			<td>no</td>			<td>yes</td>			<td>yes</td>			<td>no</td>		      </tr><tr>		      			<td> 			  <a href="#EGOCENTRIC3 Intel/Creative"> 			    <p>EGOCENTRIC3 Intel/Creative</p>			  </a>			</td> 			<td>Intel/Creative</td>			<td>no</td>			<td>no</td>			<td>yes</td>			<td>yes</td>			<td>no</td>		      </tr>		    </table>		  </div>		</div>	      </div>	      <div class="post" id="Formats">	      		<h2 class="title"> 		  <a href="/Synth-75000.tar.gz"> Formats </a> 		</h2>		<p class="meta"><span class="date">July, 2014</span><span class="posted">Posted by <a href="#">James</a></span></p>		<div style="clear: both;">&nbsp;</div>		<div class="entry">		  <p>		    The depths are stored as both 16-bit png and as floating point OpenEXR		    images. OpenEXR support is built into OpenCV and		    they can be loaded into MATLAB with the		    <a href="http://www.mit.edu/~kimo/software/matlabexr/">		    MatlabEXR </a> package. 		  </p>		  <ul>		    <li>		      raw_color_$ID.png contains the raw rgb image for		      the sample.		     		    </li>		    <li>		      registered_color_$ID.png contains the rgb image		      registered and cropped to match the depth		      image. 		    </li>		    <li>		      raw_depth_$ID.png : this is a 16-bit png image		      containing the depth values (depth measured in		      millimeters). The raw depth is not processed or		      cropped in any way.		      		    </li>		    <li>		      depth_$ID.exr : this is a floating point		      image containing the depth values (depth		      measured in centimeters)		    </li>		    <li>		      depth_$ID.png : this is a 16-bit png 		      image containing the depth values (depth		      measured in millimeters)		    </li>		  </ul>		</div>	      </div>	      <div class="post" id="CameraIntrinsics">	      		<h2 class="title"> 		  <a href="#"> Camera Intrinsics </a>		</h2>		<p class="meta"><span class="date">August, 2014</span><span class="posted">Posted by <a href="#">James</a></span></p>		<div style="clear: both;">&nbsp;</div>		<div class="entry">		  <table>		    <tr>		      <th />		      <th>Intel/Creative</th>		      <th>ASUS/Xtion</th>		    </tr>		    <tr>		      <td>Depth Camera - Horizontal Field of View</td>		      <td>74 deg</td>		      <td>58.590660</td>		    </tr>		    <tr>		      <td>Depth Camera - Vertical Field of View</td>		      <td>58 deg</td>		      <td>45.642715</td>		    </tr>		    <tr>		      <td>Color Camera - Horizontal Field of View</td>		      <td>65 deg</td>		      <td>58.590660</td>		    </tr>		    <tr>		      <td>Color Camera - Vertical Field of View</td>		      <td>54 deg</td>		      <td>45.642715</td>		    </tr>		    <tr>		      <td>Depth Resolution - Horizontal</td>		      <td>320</td>		      <td>320</td>		    </tr>		    <tr>		      <td>Depth Resolution - Vertical</td>		      <td>240</td>		      <td>240</td>		    </tr>		    <tr>		      <td>Color Resolution - Horizontal</td>		      <td>640</td>		      <td>640</td>		    </tr>		    <tr>		      <td>Color Resolution - Vertical</td>		      <td>480</td>		      <td>480</td>		    </tr>		    <tr>		      <td>Depth Focal Length</td>		      <td>224.502</td>		      <td><a href="http://web.stanford.edu/~qianyizh/projects/scenedata.html"> 525.0 </a></td>		    </tr>		    <tr>		      <td>Color Focal Length</td>		      <td>583.079</td>		      <td><a href="http://web.stanford.edu/~qianyizh/projects/scenedata.html"> 525.0 </a> </td>		    </tr>		  </table>		</div>	      </div>	      <div>		<div class="post" id="TestSequences">		  <h2 class="title"> 			    <a href="#"> Test Sequences </a>		  </h2>		  <div class="entry">		  		    <p> 		      <a href="yml_videos/EGOCENT